        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1970-09-15T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1970-09-15T15:12:00-05:00" n="40"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d40">
                <head>40. Summary of Conclusions of a Meeting of the Senior Review Group<note n="1"
                        type="source" xml:id="d40fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName
                            corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>
                        Institutional Files (H-Files), Box H–111, <gloss target="#t_SRG1"
                            >SRG</gloss> Minutes, Originals, 1970. Top Secret; Sensitive; <gloss
                            target="#t_Nodis1">Nodis</gloss>. The meeting took place in the
                        Situation Room of the White House.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            from="1970-09-15T16:12:00-04:00" to="1970-09-15T17:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 15, 1970, 4:12–5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Short-Term Cambodia Strategy (<gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss>
                        99)</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPATION</head>
                    <item>Chairman—Dr. <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Henry A. Kissinger</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>State <list>
                            <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_JUA1">U. Alexis Johnson</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_GM1">Marshall Green</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>Mr. <persName>Arthur Hartman</persName>
                            </item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <item>Defense <list>
                            <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_PD1">David Packard</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>Vice Adm. <persName corresp="#p_FWR1">William Flanagan</persName>
                            </item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss>
                        <list>
                            <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HRM1">Richard Helms</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_CGA1">George Carver</persName>
                            </item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>
                        <list>
                            <item>Adm. <persName corresp="#p_MTH1">Thomas H. Moorer</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>B/Gen. Robert Lukeman</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Staff <list>
                            <item>Dr. <persName corresp="#p_SKW1">K. Wayne Smith</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HJH1">John H. Holdridge</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>Col. <persName corresp="#p_KRT1">Richard T. Kennedy</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>Capt. <persName>Robert Sansom</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>Mr. <persName>D. Keith Guthrie</persName>
                            </item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_OMB1">OMB</gloss>
                        <list>
                            <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_SJ1">James R. Schlesinger</persName>
                            </item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p rend="center">SUMMARY OF CONCLUSIONS</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>The <gloss target="#t_SRG1">SRG</gloss> agreed that from a military
                        standpoint, Strategy 3, Variant 3, as outlined in the <gloss
                            target="#t_VSSG1">VSSG</gloss> Working Paper,<note n="2" xml:id="d40fn2"
                            >See <ref target="#d39">Document 39</ref> and <ref target="#d39fn2"
                                >footnote 2 thereto</ref>.</note> states the preferred objective,
                        which is to maintain the Cambodian Government in control of the half of the
                        country that includes the capital, populated areas, and port. The <gloss
                            target="#t_SRG1">SRG</gloss> also agreed that in seeking to achieve this
                        objective, the US should aim at building up the capabilities of the
                        Cambodian forces so as to minimize the need for significant long-term
                        intervention by the <gloss target="#t_ARVN1">ARVN</gloss>. The <gloss
                            target="#t_SRG1">SRG</gloss> noted that the requirement for involvement
                        of South Vietnamese forces in the defense of Cambodia should decline as the
                        capabilities of the Cambodian forces improve.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>To provide a fuller analysis of the implications of the strategic
                        objectives outlined in Paragraph 1, the <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>
                        Staff will prepare in chart form an analysis covering the next six months
                        which relates the expected increase in Cambodian military capabilities, the
                        likely levels of <gloss target="#t_NVA1">NVA</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_VC1"
                            >VC</gloss> reinforcements in Cambodia, and the requirements for
                        employment of South Vietnamese forces in the defense of Cambodia. <gloss
                            target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss> will assist in assessing prospective <gloss
                            target="#t_NVA1">NVA</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_VC1">VC</gloss>
                        reinforcement levels, and <pb facs="0149" n="110" xml:id="pg_110"/>
                        <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> will provide data on prospects for the
                        improvement of Cambodian military capabilities.<note n="3" xml:id="d40fn3"
                            >In a September 19 memorandum to <persName corresp="#p_PD1"
                                >Packard</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_JUA1">Johnson</persName>,
                            and <persName corresp="#p_HRM1">Helms</persName>, <persName
                                corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> requested that they expand
                            the <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 99 response to include an
                            option that would allow Cambodian forces to defend the area outlined in
                            variant 3 of Strategy 3 without “significant long term intervention by
                            South Vietnamese.” (National Archives, <persName corresp="#p_NRM1"
                                >Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                                >NSC</gloss> Files, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>
                            Institutional Files (H-Files), Box H–173, <gloss target="#t_NSSM1"
                                >NSSM</gloss> Files, <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss>
                            99)</note>
                    </item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>State and <gloss target="#t_OMB1">OMB</gloss> will prepare a study on
                        means to fund a Cambodian assistance program at the current level pending
                        passage of a supplemental appropriation or in default of passage of such an
                        appropriation. The study should also define the amount which should be
                        requested to support the objectives referred to in Paragraph 1 if it is
                        decided to seek a supplemental appropriation early in CY71.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>The <gloss target="#t_SRG1">SRG</gloss> endorsed the suggestion that the
                        Secretary of Defense provide the President his views on why he believes it
                        would be possible to obtain a supplemental appropriation for military
                        assistance to Cambodia prior to the adjournment of Congress on October
                        23.</item>
                </list>
                <p>[Omitted here are the minutes of the meeting.]</p>
            </div>
